Item_Details.Item_Response: Dr. Gordon is emphasizing the intricacy and vastness of genomes. Individuals are not the expression of a single gene. Instead individuals are the expression of genes of different species working together. In his article, "Germs Are Us," Michael Specter states that genes have been looked upon as our "biological destiny [...] When DNA is damaged or genes interact poorly with one another the eventual result is disease" (Germs Are Us). Specter indicates the role that genomes play in an individual's body. Genes determine the structure of a person and DNA works together in order to help the individual live healthily. Inadequate interaction between DNA may result in diseases. Furthermore Dr. Gordon's quote conveys the vastness of genomes in our universe. Dr. Ruebush, author of, "Why Dirt is Good," demonstrates this vastness by writing, "The typical human probably harbors some 90 trillion microbes [...] The very fact that you have so many microbes of so many different kinds is what keeps you healthy most of the time" (Wash In Moderation).

Another example is that the body consists of bacterias which is vital to the process of breaking down components and digesting the food in your stomach (Source 4).
